The cached sampler state was being persisted between device resets. After a context lost event, the GL sampler states are reset to default but the cached state was not. This meant that if your game used a single non-default sampler state, after a device reset it would never get applied.

Reproducing the problem is simple. Create a default game for Android and load a single texture that is smaller than the screen size into a `Texture2D tex` member. Then add the following drawing code. After a resume (run app, hit Home button, switch back to app), you will notice that the PointClamp sampler state is no longer being applied (texture looks smooth instead of blocky).

```
        spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.Deferred, BlendState.AlphaBlend, SamplerState.PointClamp, DepthStencilState.Default, RasterizerState.CullNone);
        Rectangle rect =  new Rectangle(0, 0, Window.Width, Window.Height);
        spriteBatch.Draw(tex, rect, null, Color.White, 0.0f, Vector2.Zero, SpriteEffects.None, 0.0f);
        spriteBatch.End();
```

Codeplex discussion: http://monogame.codeplex.com/discussions/428652

A while ago I found and posted a problem that caused a fresh empty monogame WindowsGL program to crash every time you would close it.

The fix is to wrap the Game1.cs that you create in the Program.cs class with the using keyword, I'm guessing so it disposes properly? Im not sure, but after wrapping the initalization of that class with using keyword the AccessViolationException  does not throw anymore:

using (Game1 game = new Game1())
            {
                game.Run();
            }

I think I actually tried doing this a month back, but back then it did not allow the using keyword to be used. I think IDisposable was not implemented on the Game.cs class back then.

I am working to process content and bring it in to MonoGame but have run in to a shader problem.

The shader includes a technique with parameters:
technique ColorTextureBlendTechnique
{
    pass P0
    {
        VertexShader = compile vs_2_0 SimpleVS();
        PixelShader  = compile ps_2_0 SimplePS(true, true);
    }
}

And the SimplePS function looks like this:
float4 SimplePS(VSOutput input, uniform bool useColor, uniform bool useTexture) : COLOR

This gets an error "Expected CloseParenthesis" on the PixelShader line.  If I remove the parameters and set the defaults it seems to compile:
PxelShader  = compile ps_2_0 SimplePS();
float4 SimplePS(VSOutput input, uniform bool useColor = true, uniform bool useTexture = true) : COLOR

Are parameters not supported?  I tried pulling the latest code but couldn't get 2mgfx to build. So this may already be addressed.  Thanks.
